abstract: Expanded political coverage, and a new $250 million campus worthy of a start-up, are signs of a Spanish-language network on the rise.
snippet: Expanded political coverage, and a new $250 million campus worthy of a start-up, are signs of a Spanish-language network on the rise.
lead_paragraph: MIAMI — Twenty miles west of Miami’s glittering oceanfront, closer to the Everglades than to the Fontainebleau hotel, a hangar-size office building rises from the flatlands like a spaceship.

abstract: How much joy is left to be squeezed out of watching photo-realistic animals, or new Hollywood stars, act out old movies we loved, beat for beat?
snippet: How much joy is left to be squeezed out of watching photo-realistic animals, or new Hollywood stars, act out old movies we loved, beat for beat?
lead_paragraph: Hollywood is, self-evidently, in the middle of a nostalgia boom. A time traveler from the mid-1990s who suddenly lands in the mezzanine of any given AMC theater this year should be forgiven for thinking his experiment failed as he watches audiences pour into theaters for “The Addams Family,” “The Lion King,” and “Men in Black” — all 2019 rejiggerings of two-decade-old movies.

abstract: Three shows and one new book vividly illustrate how photography and art can capture the moment, whether it’s men going to the moon or models striding a catwalk.
snippet: Three shows and one new book vividly illustrate how photography and art can capture the moment, whether it’s men going to the moon or models striding a catwalk.
lead_paragraph: NASA invited the artist Robert Rauschenberg to Cape Kennedy, Fla., for the launch of Apollo 11, the first manned spaceflight to the moon, in July 1969, hoping that the experience would inspire him to commemorate it in art.

abstract: But has he raised the political temperature too high for his own good?
snippet: But has he raised the political temperature too high for his own good?
lead_paragraph: For Democrats seeking to pry loose moderates and conservatives in 2020, the voters drawn to President Trump by their shared animosity to all things liberal are an impenetrable constituency, long gone, while more traditional Republicans offer the potential for modest support.

abstract: It remains a landmark in Berkeley, one of America’s very best bookstores and worth an epic detour to visit.
snippet: It remains a landmark in Berkeley, one of America’s very best bookstores and worth an epic detour to visit.
lead_paragraph: Moe Moskowitz, the co-founder of Moe’s Books in Berkeley, was known for a lot of things: his omnipresent cigars; his appalling dancing (sometimes to Cab Calloway on the store’s turntable); his political activism; and especially the way he held court at the cash register, riffing like Jackie Mason at a Friars Club podium.

abstract: Female candidates are climbing in the polls and dominating debates. Yet Democrats are still being asked if a woman can be elected president.
snippet: Female candidates are climbing in the polls and dominating debates. Yet Democrats are still being asked if a woman can be elected president.
lead_paragraph: GREENVILLE, S.C. — Some people whisper it, some apologize for it, and some are very careful to mention their neighbors — their neighbors would be the ones to ask.

headline_main: It’s a Question No One Says They Want to Ask. But the Women Running for President Keep Hearing It.
headline_print_headline: Six Female Candidates, One Unrelenting Refrain

abstract: Fourteen candidates are assured a place onstage. The rest are battling it out for six remaining slots. In September, things get tougher.
snippet: Fourteen candidates are assured a place onstage. The rest are battling it out for six remaining slots. In September, things get tougher.
lead_paragraph: With just four weeks to go until the second set of Democratic presidential primary debates, a handful of lower-tier candidates are in danger of missing them. A single percentage point of support in one poll could be the difference between getting invited to Detroit and being left off the debate stage.
